<dl class="specification-list">

        <dt>Identification and Creation</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
            <dt>Object Number</dt>
            <dd>CW2001.1867</dd>

                            <dt>People</dt>
                <dd>
                                                                 <a href=https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/collections/person/29410>Christopher Wilmarth</a>, American                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          (Sonoma, CA 1943 - 1987 New York, NY)
                                            <br>
                                    </dd>
            
                            <dt>Title</dt>
                <dd>Artist's documents: correspondence with California College of Arts and Crafts, 1986-1987</dd>
            
                                                                                                            
                            <dt>Classification</dt>
                <dd>Archival Material</dd>
                                        <dt>Work Type</dt>
                <dd>
                                                            archival material                                                      </dd>
                                        <dt>Date</dt>
                <dd>1986-1987</dd>
                                                                <dt>Culture</dt>
                <dd>American</dd>
                            <dt>Persistent Link</dt>
                <dd><a href="https://hvrd.art/o/95724">https://hvrd.art/o/95724</a></dd>
          </dl>
        </dd>

        
        
        
        
        
        <dt>Acquisition and Rights</dt>
        <dd>
          <dl>
                          <dt>Credit Line</dt>
              <dd>Harvard Art Museums/Fogg Museum, The Christopher Wilmarth Archive, Gift of Susan Wilmarth-Rabineau</dd>
            
                          <dt>Copyright</dt>
              <dd>© Estate of Christopher Wilmarth / Susan Wilmarth-Rabineau</dd>
            
                          <dt>Accession Year</dt>
              <dd>2001</dd>
            
            <dt>Object Number</dt>
            <dd>CW2001.1867</dd>

                          <dt>Division</dt>
              <dd>Modern and Contemporary Art</dd>
            
                          <dt>Contact</dt>
              <dd><a href="mailto:am_moderncontemporary@harvard.edu"><span>am_moderncontemporary@harvard.edu</span></a></dd>
                               		  <dd>The Harvard Art Museums encourage the use of images found on this website for personal, noncommercial use, including educational and scholarly purposes. To request a higher resolution file of this image, please submit an <a href="https://www.harvardartmuseums.org/imagerequest"><span>online request.</span></a></dd>
          </dl>
        </dd>

                  <dt>Descriptions</dt>
          <dd>
            <dl>
                              <dt>Description</dt>
                <dd>1) Typed letter on thick white CCAC stationery from Neil J. Hoffman, President, to Wilmarth expressing delight at Wilmarth's interest in establishing a scholarship for glass students. Dated March 11, 1986.<br />
<br />
2) 2 xeroxed pages of handwritten letter from Wilmarth to Hoffman describing in more detail his interest in funding a scholarship for glass students. Dated 8 May 1986.<br />
<br />
3) Double-sided handwritten draft of the above letter from Wilmarth to Hoffman in black ball-point on thin white paper.<br />
<br />
4) Typed letter on CCAC letterhead from Hoffman to Wilmarth on the topic of the projected scholarship. Dated May 21, 1986.<br />
<br />
5) Xerox of handwritten "Agreement between Chris Wilmarth + David Burton of CCAC" for the production of 2 Pate de Verre "heads" for Breath pieces. Dated 2 June 1986.<br />
<br />
6) Carbon copy of letter from Wilmarth to David Burton with notes as to the above "heads" and enclosing a 50% deposit for his work. Dated 17 June 1986. Wilmarth wrote at top in blue ball-point a "CCAC #," presumably a phone number for Burton or another contact.<br />
<br />
7) Empty CCAC envelope mailed to Wilmarth by Marvin Lipofsky. Postmarked 19 June 1986.<br />
<br />
8) Perhaps the above envelope enclosed this: xerox of a UPS receipt of a package sent to Wilmarth from Lipofsky. Note at top and other notations in black ball-point are in Lipofsky's hand.<br />
<br />
9) List pertaining to glass student scholarship in Wilmarth's hand in black ball-point on verso of blank green CCAC inter-office memo sheet.<br />
<br />
10) Draft of below letter from Wilmarth to Hoffman in blue ball-point on yellow legal paper. Dated 1 July 1986.<br />
<br />
11) 2 xeroxed pages of handwritten letter from Wilmarth to Hoffman with final details of glass student scholarship. On the second page is a xerox of the check Wilmarth enclosed. Dated 1 July 1986.<br />
<br />
12) Yellow carbon copy of shipping receipt from Porter Transcontintental Trucking, bringing 8 cardboard boxes from Marvin Lipofsky to Wilmarth. Dated 7/7/1986. <br />
<br />
13) Typed letter on CCAC letterhead to Wilmarth from Hoffman with thanks for his scholarship in memory of his brother, Peter Bell Wilmarth. Dated July 8, 1986.<br />
<br />
14) 2 pages of handwritten letter in blue ball-point on yellow legal paper from Burton to Wilmarth with details of Pate de Verre process and color samples. Dated 7/9/1986.<br />
<br />
15) Faint carbon copy of handwritten letter from Wilmarth to Burton with choice of color samples. Dated 20 July 1986. At top in black ball-point Wilmarth wrote the name Dale Johnson.<br />
<br />
16) Worn envelope to Wilmarth from Lipofsky. Enclosed are: a folded xerox with a typed quotation and 3 sketched heads, on the verso of which Lipofsky has written a brief note; a postcard showing The Maestro, apparently a performance artist and painter, with a further note from Lipofsky; and the card of Piero L. Mussi of Berkeley-based Artworks Foundry and Gallery. Envelope postmarked 26 July 1986.<br />
<br />
17) Notecard written in black ball-point from Ruth Okimoto to Wilmarth, thanking him for the gift of a Statue of Liberty figure which Lipofsky also mentioned in one of the two above notes. Okimoto appears to be Lipofsky's wife and a painter; the note also includes family details. Dated July 27, 1986.<br />
<br />
18) Handwritten letter in black ink on thin cream paper from Burton to Wilmarth acknowledging a final letter and check from Wilmarth and sending along some last details of the process and how the colors of the "heads" will alter based on handling. Dated 10/27/1986. With original envelope.<br />
<br />
19) Cream sheet of paper on which Wilmarth has written in blue ball-point the following list: "4 glass castings / 1 plaster mold / 2 Pate de Verre / 2 [blank]." Undated.<br />
<br />
20) Various scribbled names and phone numbers on 4 scraps of paper, all but one in Wilmarth's hand. On a fifth scrap are Wilmarth's notes in graphite for a particular casting process.<br />
<br />
21) Empty CCAC envelope, postmarked May 23, 1986, and sent to Wilmarth from Hoffman, but now bearing notes in black ink in Wilmarth's hand about a meal on a flight from Denver that contained broken glass. <br />
<br />
22) Stack of paperclipped papers in fragment of an original envelope, however said papers (and obviously the envelope) have all been torn in half. Seems to have been a note from Lipofsky to Wilmarth which enclosed a number of xeroxed letters about other glass scholarships at CCAC [i.e. not Wilmarth's]. All such letters are dated the fall of 1986. It is unclear precisely why Lipofsky is sending them to Wilmarth, however in his note he confirms that he is "going forward with [his] legal action toward CCAC" and says he may ask Wilmarth for a deposition if he's willing. Note dated bizarrely Oct 30 / Sept 1, but postmarked August 31, 1987.<br />
<br />
23) Other half of above torn envelope. This is the half that bears the postmark and also a note, probably from Lipofsky, in red ink naming a woman interested in Wilmarth's work for a museum (the name itself has been torn from the envelope).<br />
<br />
<br />
</dd>
                                                       </dl>
          </dd>
        
        
        
                  <dt>Subjects and Contexts</dt>
          <dd>
                          <p>Wilmarth</p>
                      </dd>
        

        
      
      
        
